e browser` should either:\n1. Extract meaningful content from the Google Docs page (e.g., via `DOCS_modelChunk` interception as proposed in #72), or\n2. Fall back to the export API with a warning, preserving images and content\n\n## Actual behavior\n\n`--capture browser` navigates to the `/edit` page, but Google Docs uses canvas-based rendering with no DOM content. The result:\n\n- **All images are lost** (0 images vs 30-37 with `--capture api`)\n- **Content is drastically reduced** (8-11 KB vs 19-23 KB)\n- **Table structure is lost or degraded**\n\n### Test results (Doc 1 — tables with images)\n\n| Capture flag | Lines | Size | Images |\n|-------------|-------|------|--------|\n| `--capture api` | 327 | 19,257 bytes | 37 |\n| `--capture browser` | 290 | 10,947 bytes | **0** |\n\n### Test results (Doc 2 — tables with images and links)\n\n| Capture flag | Lines | Size | Images |\n|-------------|-------|------|--------|\n| `--capture api` | 10 | 23,359 bytes | 30 |\n| `--capture browser` | 124 | 8,120 bytes | **0** |\n\n## Tested with\n\n- `@link-assistant/web-capture` v1.7.6 (internal 0.3.0)\n- `--engine playwright`\n- Two different public Google Docs with tables, images, and links\n- Archive format\n\n## Root cause\n\nGoogle Docs `/edit` page renders content via `<canvas>` — there is no HTML DOM with text or `<img>` elements for the browser capture to extract. The JS CLI correctly launches a browser (unlike the Rust version, see #80), but the resulting page has no extractable DOM content.\n\n## Possible solutions\n\n1. **Short-term**: When `--capture browser` detects a Google Docs URL and finds no meaningful DOM content, fall back to `--capture api` with a warning\n2. **Long-term**: Implement `DOCS_modelChunk` interception as described in #72 to extract the full document model from the `/edit` page","createdAt":"2026-04-17T20:44:54Z","number":81,"state":"OPEN","title":"JS: --capture browser on Google Docs drops all images and loses content"}","matches":[{"indices":[